04784nam a22005535i 9780226198262DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014014262  a97802261982627 a10.7208/97802261982622doi  a(DE-B1597)568260  a(OCoLC)1226679198  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK271b.B36 2015 4aJK271b.B36 2015 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a352.3/809731 aBaumgartner, Frank R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Information :bProblem Definition and the Course of Public Policy in America /cBryan D. Jones, Frank R. Baumgartner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b48 figures, 8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I “Seek and Ye Shall Find” -- t1 Search, Information, and Policy Agendas -- t2 Organizing for Expertise or Organizing for Complexity? -- t3 Information, Search, and Government -- tPart II Information and the Growth of Government -- t4 The Rise and Decline of Institutional Information Processing in the Executive and Legislative Branches -- t5 From Clarity to Complexity in Congress -- t6 The Search for Information and the Great New-Issue Expansion -- t7 The Thickening and Broadening of Government -- t8 Rounding Up the Usual Political Suspects -- tPart III The Implications of Information in Government -- t9 Organizing Information and the Transformation of U.S. Policy Making -- t10 Organizing Complexity -- tAppendices: Appendix to Chapter 4 -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow does the government decide what’s a problem and what isn’t? And what are the consequences of that process? Like individuals, Congress is subject to the “paradox of search.” If policy makers don’t look for problems, they won’t find those that need to be addressed. But if they carry out a thorough search, they will almost certainly find new problems—and with the definition of each new problem comes the possibility of creating a government program to address it. With The Politics of Attention, leading policy scholars Frank R. Baumgartner and Bryan D. Jones demonstrated the central role attention plays in how governments prioritize problems. Now, with The Politics of Information, they turn the focus to the problem-detection process itself, showing how the growth or contraction of government is closely related to how it searches for information and how, as an organization, it analyzes its findings. Better search processes that incorporate more diverse viewpoints lead to more intensive policymaking activity. Similarly, limiting search processes leads to declines in policy making. At the same time, the authors find little evidence that the factors usually thought to be responsible for government expansion—partisan control, changes in presidential leadership, and shifts in public opinion—can be systematically related to the patterns they observe. Drawing on data tracing the course of American public policy since World War II, Baumgartner and Jones once again deepen our understanding of the dynamics of American policy making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFederal governmentxInformation resources managementxUnited States. 0aFederal governmentxInformation resources managementzUnited States. 0aPolicy sciencesxUnited States. 0aPolicy scienceszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aJones, Bryan D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps